@becketqin I did some test and it seems `Condition.signalAll()` will not clear the flag, however `Condition.await()` can potentially throw the exception and clear the flag, my test code:

```
        Thread.currentThread().interrupt();

        assertTrue(Thread.currentThread().isInterrupted());

        try {
            Thread.sleep(1);
            fail("will never get here");
        } catch (InterruptedException e) {
            assertFalse(Thread.currentThread().isInterrupted());
            Thread.currentThread().interrupt();
        }

        assertTrue(Thread.currentThread().isInterrupted());

        ReentrantLock lock = new ReentrantLock();
        Condition cond = lock.newCondition();

        lock.lock();

        cond.signalAll();

        assertTrue(Thread.currentThread().isInterrupted());

        try {
            cond.await();
        } catch (InterruptedException e) {
            // do nothing
        }

        lock.unlock();

        assertFalse(Thread.currentThread().isInterrupted());
```

@guozhangwang , my test was a little bit different. And I saw interesting behavior.
The following code prints _true_ then _false_.

```
public static void main(String[] args) {
        final ReentrantLock lock = new ReentrantLock();
        final Condition cond = lock.newCondition();
        Thread t = new Thread() {
            @Override
            public void run() {
                lock.lock();
                // When interrupt() is called, the thread will not wake up, but its interrupt flag will be set.
                cond.awaitUninterruptibly();
                lock.unlock();
            }
        };
        t.start();
        t.interrupt();
        // We interrupt the thread here, the thread does not wake up but the interrupted flag should be set.
        System.out.println(t.isInterrupted()); // This line prints true
        // wake up the thread after interrupt the thread.
        lock.lock();
        cond.signalAll();
        // Check if the signal all clears the interrupt flag.
        System.out.println(t.isInterrupted()); // this line prints false
    }
```

The above code means cond.signalAll() clears the interrupt flag. Notice we did not release the lock in the main thread.

If we release the lock in main thread the result becomes interesting. The following code prints _(true, false, false), (true, true, false), (true, true, true)_ randomly. 

```
    public static void main(String[] args) throws InterruptedException {
        final ReentrantLock lock = new ReentrantLock();
        final Condition cond = lock.newCondition();
        Thread t = new Thread() {
            @Override
            public void run() {
                lock.lock();
                // When interrupt() is called, the thread will not wake up, but its interrupt flag will be set.
                cond.awaitUninterruptibly();
                lock.unlock();
            }
        };
        t.start();
        t.interrupt();
        // We interrupt the thread here, the thread does not wake up but the interrupted flag should be set.
        System.out.println(t.isInterrupted());
        // wake up the thread after interrupt the thread.
        lock.lock();
        cond.signalAll();
        // Check if the signal all clears the interrupt flag.
        System.out.println(t.isInterrupted());
        lock.unlock();
        System.out.println(t.isInterrupted());
    }
```

This is quite strange because the later lock.unlock() changes the result on the previous line of printing. 

If we add a `Thread.sleep()` in the main thread after `lock.unlock`. The following code gives either _(true, true, false)_ or _(true, false, false)_.

```
    public static void main(String[] args) throws InterruptedException {
        final ReentrantLock lock = new ReentrantLock();
        final Condition cond = lock.newCondition();
        Thread t = new Thread() {
            @Override
            public void run() {
                lock.lock();
                // When interrupt() is called, the thread will not wake up, but its interrupt flag will be set.
                cond.awaitUninterruptibly();
                lock.unlock();
            }
        };
        t.start();
        t.interrupt();
        // We interrupt the thread here, the thread does not wake up but the interrupted flag should be set.
        System.out.println(t.isInterrupted());
        // wake up the thread after interrupt the thread.
        lock.lock();
        cond.signalAll();
        // Check if the signal all clears the interrupt flag.
        System.out.println(t.isInterrupted());
        lock.unlock();
        Thread.sleep(1);
        System.out.println(t.isInterrupted());
    }
```

So it looks to me that the behavior of calling `signalAll()` after calling `interrupt()` is not deterministic. But `signalAll()` does eventually clear the interrupt flag.

