@becketqin I tried your code locally, and actually the first program can return {true, true} or {false, false} or {true, false} as well. After digging into Condition I think this is not because of some random behavior of `signalAll()` but `awaitUninterruptibly()`:

```
public final void awaitUninterruptibly() {
            Node node = addConditionWaiter();
            int savedState = fullyRelease(node);
            boolean interrupted = false;
            while (!isOnSyncQueue(node)) {
                LockSupport.park(this);
                if (Thread.interrupted())
                    interrupted = true;
            }
            if (acquireQueued(node, savedState) || interrupted)
                selfInterrupt();
        }
```

Note that it triggers `Thread.interrupted()` every time it returns from parking the thread (which may be returning at any point of time), and only re-set the flag through `selfInterrupt()` at the end of the call. 

So if the call ordering is

```
t.interrupt();                            // main thread
System.out.println(t.isInterrupted());    // main thread
Thread.interrupted();              // t thread
System.out.println(t.isInterrupted());    // main thread
selfInterrupt();     // t thread
```

output is {true, false}, and if call ordering is

```
t.interrupt();                            // main thread
Thread.interrupted();              // t thread
System.out.println(t.isInterrupted());    // main thread
System.out.println(t.isInterrupted());    // main thread
selfInterrupt();     // t thread
```

output is {false, false}, and if call ordering is

```
t.interrupt();                            // main thread
Thread.interrupted();              // t thread
selfInterrupt();     // t thread
System.out.println(t.isInterrupted());    // main thread
System.out.println(t.isInterrupted());    // main thread
```

output is {true, true}. Unfortunately I did not find any better way to validate this, but I did find other functions like "Lock.lock() / unlock(), Condition.signallAll()" never modifies the corresponding thread's flag.

